I"–
<p>The archive of Radio HaÃ¯ti-Inter, currently being processed at Duke Universityâ€™s Rubenstein Rare Book and Manuscript Library, is perhaps the most comprehensive archive of late-twentieth-century Haitian history, society, and culture. The collection spans the mid-1960s through 2003 and comprises more than thirty-six hundred reel-to-reel and cassette tapes (which contain more than fifty-two hundred audio files), as well as a handful of DATs, VHS and Betacam tapes, and an estimated one hundred linear feet of paper. Under the direction of Jean Dominique and MichÃ¨le Montas, Radio Haiti broadcast the news, investigative reporting, interviews, and incisive editorials, exposing repression, corruption, impunity, and exclusion, from the days of the Duvalier dictatorship through military rule and coups dâ€™Ã©tat to the early promises and eventual disenchantments of the democratic era.</p>

<p>In 2013, Montas donated the archives of Radio Haiti to Duke, under the condition that the collection be made accessible to people <em>in Haiti</em>. The creation of this publicly accessible, multilingual, audio archiveâ€”this complex and inexact process of unsilencing, of bringing history and memory home via a digital spaceâ€”demands that we rethink what a university library can do and whom it aims to serve.</p>

<h2 id="the-story-of-radio-haiti">The Story of Radio Haiti</h2>

<p>When Jean Dominique, the outspoken and charismatic director of Radio HaÃ¯ti-Inter, and his professional partner and wife, MichÃ¨le Montas, landed at the airport in Port-au-Prince on 4 March 1986, an estimated sixty thousand people were there to greet them. Photographs and video from that day show Dominiqueâ€”a man ever unflappableâ€”looking stunned.</p>

<p>They had been away, along with the rest of Radio Haitiâ€™s team, since Jean-Claude Duvalier famously declared, â€œLe bal est finiâ€ (â€œThe party is overâ€), and cracked down on the independent press and human rights activists on 28 November 1980. Dominique took refuge in the Venezuelan embassy, since Jean-Claude Duvalier had issued an order that he be killed on sight. The other journalists of Radio Haiti were arrested, imprisoned at the Casernes Dessalines, and then exiled with nothing more than the clothes on their backs. They were able to return to Haiti only after the regime fell in 1986. That March day at the airport, the crowd lifted Dominique onto their shoulders, and virtually carried the car to Radio Haitiâ€™s old station building, on Rue du Quai in downtown Port-au-Prince.</p>

<!-- _includes/image.html -->

<div class="image-wrapper">
    
        <img src="/fr/images/issue02/march1986_01.jpg" alt="Crowd Greeting Jean Dominique and MichÃ¨le Montas, 4 March 1986" />
    
        
<span class="caption">Signs include, "Long live HaÃ¯ti-Inter, we havenâ€™t forgotten," "Long live the free press," "The people have pulled off the muzzle," and "Thank you, R. Brisson."</span>
    
</div>

<p>Duvalierâ€™s militia, the dreaded Tontons Macoutes, had destroyed the station. The equipment was smashed or stolen, the safe had been broken into, and Dominiqueâ€™s office had been ransacked. But Radio Haitiâ€™s tapes had not been destroyed. J. J. Dominique, Jeanâ€™s daughter and Radio Haitiâ€™s station manager, <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20170904034711/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-18Ha_A-KuU">describes</a> how the archive came to be, how it survived, and how the journalists salvaged all the tapes they could:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Radyo Ayiti se youn nan kote enpÃ²tans achiv egziste depi lontan. PwoblÃ¨m peyi d Ayiti, poutÃ¨t yon pakÃ¨t rezon, anpil enstitisyon pa gen achiv. Donk, nan radyo a, ant 1970, lÃ¨ Jean kÃ²manse radyo a kÃ²m radyo pa l, epi lÃ¨ MichÃ¨le kÃ²manse vin travay nan radyo a, yo te kenbe achiv. Sa vle di repÃ²taj, emisyon kiltirÃ¨l, editoryalâ€”tout sa k ap fÃ¨t nan radyo a ki enpÃ²tan, yo kenbe yo. E lÃ¨ gouvÃ¨nman Duvalier a voye kraze radyo a, nou toujou di, â€œMakout yo, yo konn kraze, men yo pa konn valÃ¨ yon seri de bagay.â€ Sa vle di yo t ap chÃ¨che lajan. Yo kase kÃ²f radyo a pou wÃ¨ si te gen lajan. Men yo pa panse, yo pa reflechi, ke bagay ki te gen plis valÃ¨ nan radyo a se travay achiv radyo a. Sa ki fÃ¨, an 1986 lÃ¨ n al relouvri radyo aÂ .Â .Â . tout achiv yo te la. Tout anrejistreman, bann mayetik, kasÃ¨t, menm plak yo pa vole. Donk, nou rekipere tout bagay sa yo.Â .Â .Â . Evidaman, yo te nan yon eta! Pousye, etsetera! Nou bije pase anpil tan ap netwaye! Nou te konn netwaye plak yo nan gwo kivÃ¨t! Yo netwaye plak yo grenn-an-grenn! Nou netwaye plak yo nan kivÃ¨t. Donk tout achiv yo, nou repran yo.Â .Â .Â . Bon, genyen ki te tÃ¨lman nan yon move eta, nou pa t kapab kenbe yo. DabÃ² yo te twÃ² vye. Yo te fin kase bout-bout. Nou pa t konn gwo teknik ki te ka pemÃ¨t nou kenbe yo. Genyen ki te nan yon move eta men nou reyisi kopye yo. Donk, nou fÃ¨ sa nou te kapab pou achiv soti 1970 rive 1980, lÃ¨ radyo a te kraze.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>(Radio Haiti was one of the few places that long recognized the importance of archives. The problem is that in Haiti, for many reasons, there are many institutions that donâ€™t have archives. So at the station, from 1970, when Jean took ownership of the station, and when MichÃ¨le came to work at the station, they kept their archives. Thatâ€™s to say reportage, cultural programs, editorialsâ€”everything important that was done at the station, they kept it. And when the Duvalier government came to destroy the station, as we always said, â€œThe Macoutes, they may destroy, but they donâ€™t know the true value of so many things.â€ That is to say, they were looking for money. They broke the stationâ€™s safe to see if there was money inside. But they didnâ€™t think, they didnâ€™t understand that the most valuable thing at the station was the work contained in the stationâ€™s archive. So in 1986, when we went to reopen the stationÂ .Â .Â . the whole archive was still there.Â .Â .Â . We recovered all of it. Of course, they were in a state! Dust, etc.! We had to spend a lot of time cleaning them! We cleaned the disks in big basins, we cleaned the disks one by one, we cleaned the disks in those basins.Â .Â .Â . Well, some were in such bad condition we couldnâ€™t keep them. First, they were too old, some of them were just falling apart, and we didnâ€™t know any fancy techniques that would allow us to keep them. Some were in bad shape, but we managed to copy them. So we did what we could, for the archive spanning 1970 to 1980, when the station was destroyed.)<sup id="fnref:1" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup></p>
</blockquote>

<p>Over the next seven months, Radio Haiti launched a â€œsolidarity campaignâ€ to raise money to rebuild the stationâ€”it collected small sums, cent by cent, donated by ordinary Haitian people, many of whom had very little, and all of whom felt that Radio Haiti was theirs.</p>

<!-- _includes/image.html -->

